WRITING.TITLE: What an episode!
WRITING.TEXT: I just finished watching today's episode; and I'm utterly lost for words (I rewrote this post at least 3 times!). So I'll keep it short: I cried. This episode broke my heart, and I fucking loved it. This melancholy, this nugget of sadness, I will cherish this for as long as possible. Thank you, truly, everybody who has worked on Horace and Pete. And thank you Louis CK. You really got me at Louie, and you've got me again at Horace and Pete. Thank you.
[r/lifehacks](https://www.reddit.com/r/lifehacks/) is going to be thrilled.

WRITING.TITLE: Yet another "I just finished Death Note" post.
WRITING.TEXT: Just finished binge watching Death Note. I'm ... dazed, to say the least. Episodes one through twenty-five (the L arc) were simply amazing. I'm still undecided on whether the ending was forced or brilliant (leaning towards the former), but it was definitely an incredible ride. Initially having written off Death Note as just another typical fantasy-fulfillment anime, I've never been happier to have been proven wrong. Here's hoping Netflix does it some justice.
Right. I sort of feel the same. I'd have much preferred Light to have "won the battle, but lost the war", i.e. to have defeated Near but eventually gone crazy with boredom/power.

That's an interesting take. However, it is debatable whether Light having Mikami pinned down as a constant is forced writing or not. I'd like to think Light would've been more cautious, however the time-jump has made me doubtful.

gt;Although I loved the way Light devolved when he got "found out" and he started really losing himself, becoming incomprehensible and insane due to the mere idea that he lost. That was pretty great to see. Yes, definitely!
Haven't had the pleasure of reading the manga, will start once I'm a little less busy!
While I can sympathize to a certain extent, you not liking Light and the ending being forced are objectively two different things.
